# Lantern OS — AI Agent Rules (Anti-Slop Ruleset)
# Applies to all AI assistants working in this repository.
# These rules are non-negotiable. Bypass requires explicit user instruction.

## Dependency Minimalism
- Do NOT add npm or pip packages without explicit user approval
- Prefer built-in Node.js / Python stdlib before reaching for a library
- If a package is needed, state the name, why nothing existing covers it, and the license

## Atomic Changes
- One logical change per commit — do not bundle unrelated fixes
- If a task requires touching > 3 files for unrelated reasons, split into separate commits
- Never refactor surrounding code that is not related to the task

## No Boilerplate Generation
- Do not generate scaffold, starter, or template files unless explicitly asked
- Do not add README, CHANGELOG, or documentation files unless the task requires it
- Do not add TODO comments as output — either fix it now or do not mention it in code

## No Hallucinated APIs
- Only call functions, methods, and endpoints that provably exist in this repo or its declared dependencies
- If unsure whether an API exists, read the source file before using it
- Never invent a module path — use Glob or Grep to verify the file exists first

## No File Duplication
- Before creating a new file, search for an existing one that covers the same concern
- Before writing a new function, grep for an existing one with the same signature
- If a near-duplicate exists, extend or refactor it rather than creating a second copy

## Security (OWASP Top 10 Minimum)
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, tokens, or passwords in any file
- Always validate and sanitize user input at system boundaries (HTTP requests, CLI args)
- Never use eval(), exec(), or shell interpolation with user-controlled strings
- Use parameterised queries or ORM methods — never build SQL by string concatenation
- Set Content-Security-Policy, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options on all HTTP responses
- Do not disable TLS verification or accept self-signed certs in production paths

## No Debug Pollution
- Do not commit console.log(), print(), debugger, pdb.set_trace(), or breakpoint() calls
- Remove all debug output before committing — use proper logging (console.error, Python logging)

## Scope Discipline
- Do not fix bugs, refactor, or add features beyond what the task explicitly requires
- If you notice an adjacent issue while working, log it as a GitHub Issue — do not fix it inline
- One PR per agent lane (see CLAUDE.md Workstream Rule)

## Commit Message Quality
- Format: type(scope): short description (≤ 72 chars)
- Body: explain WHY, not WHAT
- No "wip", "fix", "update", "changes", "temp", "placeholder"
- No emojis unless the user asks for them

## Verification Before Claiming Done
- Run the affected code path, not just tests, before reporting a task complete
- If a UI change was made, confirm it renders correctly in the browser
- If a server route was added, confirm it returns the expected HTTP status
